T1  - Market Discipline and Systemic Risk
AU  - Morrison, Alan D.
AU  - Walther, Ansgar
Y1  - 2019/10/24
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3248
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3248
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 764
EP  - 782
VL  - 66
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We analyze a general equilibrium model in which financial institutions generate endogenous systemic risk. Banks optimally select correlated investments and thereby expose themselves to fire-sale risk so as to sharpen their incentives. Systemic risk is therefore a natural consequence of banks? fundamental role as delegated monitors. Our model sheds light on recent and historical trends in measured systemic risk. Technological innovations and government-directed lending can cause surges in systemic risk. Strict capital requirements and well-designed government-asset purchase programs can combat systemic risk.This paper was accepted by Gustavo Manso, finance.
