TY  - JOUR
T1  - Effects of a Tournament Incentive Plan Incorporating Managerial Discretion in a Geographically Dispersed Organization
AU  - Deller, Carolyn
AU  - Sandino, Tatiana
Y1  - 2019/08/12
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3214
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3214
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 911
EP  - 931
VL  - 66
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Using retail chain data, we study the effects of a tournament incentive plan based primarily on objective performance, but incorporating managerial discretion in the selection of winners. In principle, such plans could motivate employees to perform both at a high level, based on objective criteria, and in accordance with company values, considered via managerial discretion. However, such plans could be counterproductive if enough participants (especially those who do not win) perceive that subjectivity (introduced via discretion) adds unfairness. We show that, on average, the tournament incentive plan was associated with improved store sales. We also find that such plans can be more beneficial for geographically distant participants, where the potential for improving alignment is greater. Lastly, we find some evidence that participants? resource constraints (potentially affecting unfairness concerns) can impact outcomes under the plan.This paper was accepted by Shiva Rajgopal, accounting.
AB  - Using retail chain data, we study the effects of a tournament incentive plan based primarily on objective performance, but incorporating managerial discretion in the selection of winners. In principle, such plans could motivate employees to perform both at a high level, based on objective criteria, and in accordance with company values, considered via managerial discretion. However, such plans could be counterproductive if enough participants (especially those who do not win) perceive that subjectivity (introduced via discretion) adds unfairness. We show that, on average, the tournament incentive plan was associated with improved store sales. We also find that such plans can be more beneficial for geographically distant participants, where the potential for improving alignment is greater. Lastly, we find some evidence that participants? resource constraints (potentially affecting unfairness concerns) can impact outcomes under the plan.This paper was accepted by Shiva Rajgopal, accounting.
